"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The code incorrectly uses the library scikit-learn because the OneHotEncoder in the ColumnTransformer will output an array with more features than the original DataFrame. However, the GaussianNB classifier does not handle the new features correctly if they have more than two values. But the main issue here is that the GaussianNB classifier expects numeric data but the OneHotEncoder outputs categorical data which is numeric but needs to be treated with care. The correct way to use it would be to use a classifier that can handle categorical data or to specify correctly the type of data that the classifier will receive.\",\n  \"patch\": \"26c26\\n< ('algo', GaussianNB())\\n---\\n> ('algo', GaussianNB(priors=None))\\nHowever, a better solution would be to use a classifier that can handle categorical data. Here is an example using the CategoricalNB classifier:\\n25c25,26\\n< ('algo', GaussianNB())\\n---\\n> from sklearn.naive_bayes import CategoricalNB\\n> ('algo', CategoricalNB())\"\n}"